## The Specification and When to Update It

### Where the spec lives

- **Main specification**: `docs/gnucash_email_receipt_categorization_spec.mdc`
  - Domain rules (§3), inputs/outputs (§4), components (§6), evidence matching (§7), review and apply behaviour (§9–10), acceptance criteria (§15).
- **Implementation notes**: Spec §6.2.1 documents guaranteed behaviours (e.g. `get_tree()` / `get_account_path` defaults, JSONL skip-on-error, review non-fatal error handling) that are tested but not spelled out in the main narrative.

### When to update the spec

- **New feature or user-visible behaviour**: Add or amend the relevant section (scope, component, or workflow) so the spec still describes the system.
- **Behaviour change** (e.g. new error handling, new default): Update the spec (or §6.2.1) so it matches the implementation; add or adjust tests to lock in the new behaviour.
- **Implementation detail** that callers or tests rely on (e.g. “load_metadata returns None for missing/corrupt”): Prefer documenting it in §6.2.1 and covering it with tests rather than leaving it only in code.

### Relationship to tests

- The **test plan** (`docs/test_plan_and_strategy.mdc`) maps test files to spec sections and lists “Spec coverage” and “Error handling / graceful degradation”.
- When you add tests for a new requirement or error path, update the test plan (test matrix and, if needed, the spec-coverage bullets) so the next developer can see what is covered.

